{"title_page": "Hendrik Voogd", "text_new": "{{short description|Dutch painter and printmaker}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Hendrik Voogd\n| image            = Portrait of Hendrik Voogd.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1768|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Amsterdam]], [[Dutch Republic]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1839|9|4|1768|7|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Rome]], [[Papal States]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n\n'''Hendrik Voogd''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266\u025bndr\u026ak \u02c8fo\u02d0xt}};<ref>''Voogd'' in isolation: {{IPA-nl|\u02c8vo\u02d0xt|}}.</ref> 10 July 1768 \u2013 4 September 1839) was a Dutch painter and printmaker, who was active in Italy.\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Hendrik Voogd - Italian landscape with Umbrella Pines.jpg|thumb|''Italian Landscape with Umbrella Pines'' (1807) in the collection of the [[Rijksmuseum]]]]\n\nHendrik Voogd was born on 10 July 1768 in [[Amsterdam]] in the [[Dutch Republic]].<ref name=\"rkd\">[https://rkd.nl/explore/artists/81766 Hendrik Voogd], [[Netherlands Institute for Art History]], 2014. Retrieved on 10 February 2015.</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1783, Voogd studied at a local Academy and then later apprenticed under the wallpaper painter [[Jurriaan Andriessen (artist)|Jurriaan Andriessen]]. The financial aid of the Amsterdam art collector D. Versteegh (1751\u20131822) enabled him to depart in 1788 for Rome to obtain further training in landscape painting.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/hendrik-voogd-2|title=Hendrik Voogd Brief Bio|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile in Italy, Voogd befriended many famous landscape painters, such as [[Nicolas-Didier Boguet]], [[Johann Christian Reinhart]] and [[Johann Martin von Rohden]].<ref name=\"ref1\" /> Little is known about his life. He remained in Italy apart from a short visit to the Netherlands in 1828. He never married and is not known to have had any children.<ref name=Muller>{{cite book|author=Muller, Sheila D. |title=Dutch Art: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B21qT8Wuk0AC&pg=PA348-IA132 |year=2013 |publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-49581-7 |page=348}}</ref> Voogd died on 4 September 1839 in [[Rome]] in the [[Papal States]].<ref name=\"rkd\"/> From his obituary, it seems he was considered to be an old-fashioned artist of little influence. The discovery in 1959 of about two hundred of his drawings in [[Duivenvoorde Castle]] in [[South Holland]] revived interest in his work.<ref name=Muller/>\n\n== Work ==\n[[File:Voogd-Passage du gu\u00e9.JPG|thumb|''Passage at the ford'' (1819) in the collection of [[Mus\u00e9e Fabre]]]]\n\nIt is apparent, from one of his infrequent letters home, that Voogd made numerous drawings of Rome and its surroundings, including [[Tivoli, Lazio]], [[Lake Albano]], [[Castel Gandolfo]], and [[Lake Nemi]]. Some of these drawings, executed mostly in pencil and black chalk, consist of motifs taken directly from nature, such as trees and rocks; others portray views. \n\nVoogd's works from his first Roman years are primarily drawings with colored wash in the typical late 18th-century linear style. One of his major influences was [[Claude Lorrain]]. Due to the similarities in style he was nicknamed the 'Dutch Claude Lorrain'.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rijksmuseum.nl/en/search/objecten?q=Hendrik+Voogd&p=1&ps=12#/SK-A-4688,0|title=Hendrik Voogd Rijksmuseum Bio and Works|accessdate=1 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417140448/https://www.rijksmuseum.nl/en/search/objecten?q=Hendrik+Voogd&p=1&ps=12#/SK-A-4688,0|archivedate=17 April 2014}}</ref> However, in spite of these influences Voogd still retained influences from his Dutch heritage. He experimented with unusual lighting effects and luxuriant foliage, and from 1806 onwards <!-- Italian --> cattle began to feature prominently in his drawings and paintings. Some of his works can be found at the [[Rijksmuseum]].<ref name=\"ref2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Hendrik Voogd}}\n\n{{Authority control}} <!-- 89712884 is a duplicate VIAF -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voogd, Hendrik}}\n[[Category:1768 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch male painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch painter and printmaker}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Hendrik Voogd\n| image            = Portrait of Hendrik Voogd.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!--only use if different from name-->\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1768|7|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Amsterdam]], [[Dutch Republic]]\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1839|9|4|1768|7|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Rome]], [[Papal States]]\n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| known_for        = \n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} -->\n| module           =\n}}\n\n'''Hendrik Voogd''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266\u025bndr\u026ak \u02c8fo\u02d0xt}};<ref>''Voogd'' in isolation: {{IPA-nl|\u02c8vo\u02d0xt|}}.</ref> 10 July 1768 \u2013 4 September 1839) was a Dutch painter and printmaker, who was active in Italy.\n\n== Life ==\n[[File:Hendrik Voogd - Italian landscape with Umbrella Pines.jpg|thumb|''Italian Landscape with Umbrella Pines'' (1807) in the collection of the [[Rijksmuseum]]]]\n\nHendrik Voogd was born on 10 July 1768 in [[Amsterdam]] in the [[Dutch Republic]].<ref name=\"rkd\">[https://rkd.nl/explore/artists/81766 Hendrik Voogd], [[Netherlands Institute for Art History]], 2014. Retrieved on 10 February 2015.</ref>\n\nBeginning in 1783, Voogd studied at a local Academy and then later apprenticed under the wallpaper painter [[Jurriaan Andriessen (artist)|Jurriaan Andriessen]]. The financial aid of the Amsterdam art collector D. Versteegh (1751\u20131822) enabled him to depart in 1788 for Rome to obtain further training in landscape painting.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/hendrik-voogd-2|title=Hendrik Voogd Brief Bio|accessdate=1 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile in Italy, Voogd befriended many famous landscape painters, such as [[Nicolas-Didier Boguet]], [[Johann Christian Reinhart]] and [[Johann Martin von Rohden]].<ref name=\"ref1\" /> Little is known about his life. He remained in Italy apart from a short visit to the Netherlands in 1828. He never married and is not known to have had any children.<ref name=Muller>{{cite book|author=Muller, Sheila D. |title=Dutch Art: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B21qT8Wuk0AC&pg=PA348-IA132 |year=2013 |publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-49581-7 |page=348}}</ref> Voogd died on 4 September 1839 in [[Rome]] in the [[Papal States]].<ref name=\"rkd\"/> From his obituary, it seems he was considered to be an old-fashioned artist of little influence. The discovery in 1959 of about two hundred of his drawings in [[Duivenvoorde Castle]] in [[South Holland]] revived interest in his work.<ref name=Muller/>\n\n== Work ==\n[[File:Voogd-Passage du gu\u00e9.JPG|thumb|''Passage at the ford'' (1819) in the collection of [[Mus\u00e9e Fabre]]]]\n\nIt is apparent, from one of his infrequent letters home, that Voogd made numerous drawings of Rome and its surroundings, including [[Tivoli, Lazio]], [[Lake Albano]], [[Castel Gandolfo]], and [[Lake Nemi]]. Some of these drawings, executed mostly in pencil and black chalk, consist of motifs taken directly from nature, such as trees and rocks; others portray views. \n\nVoogd's works from his first Roman years are primarily drawings with colored wash in the typical late 18th-century linear style. One of his major influences was [[Claude Lorrain]]. Due to the similarities in style he was nicknamed the 'Dutch Claude Lorrain'.<ref name=\"ref2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rijksmuseum.nl/en/search/objecten?q=Hendrik+Voogd&p=1&ps=12#/SK-A-4688,0|title=Hendrik Voogd Rijksmuseum Bio and Works|accessdate=1 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417140448/https://www.rijksmuseum.nl/en/search/objecten?q=Hendrik+Voogd&p=1&ps=12#/SK-A-4688,0|archivedate=17 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> However, in spite of these influences Voogd still retained influences from his Dutch heritage. He experimented with unusual lighting effects and luxuriant foliage, and from 1806 onwards <!-- Italian --> cattle began to feature prominently in his drawings and paintings. Some of his works can be found at the [[Rijksmuseum]].<ref name=\"ref2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Hendrik Voogd}}\n\n{{Authority control}} <!-- 89712884 is a duplicate VIAF -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voogd, Hendrik}}\n[[Category:1768 births]]\n[[Category:1839 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch painters]]\n[[Category:Dutch male painters]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hendrik_Voogd"}
{"title_page": "Michel Roux", "text_new": "{{short description|French chef}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name           = Michel Roux\n| image          = Michel Roux.jpg\n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = Michel Roux in 2008\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|4|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Charolles]], France\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|3|11|1941|4|19}}\n| death_place    = [[Bray, Berkshire]], England\n| ratings        = {{plainlist|\n*[[Michelin star]]s {{Rating|3|3}} (1974&ndash;2002)\n}}\n| prevrests      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Le Gavroche]]\n*[[The Waterside Inn]]\n}}\n| awards         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Meilleur Ouvrier de France]]\n*2008 Lifetime Achievement award by ''[[Tatler (1901)|Tatler]]''\n*2011 Lifetime Achievement award by ''[[The Observer Food Monthly]]''\n}}\n| website = {{Official URL|http://www.michelroux-obe.com}}\n}}\n'''Michel Roux''', [[OBE]] ({{IPA-fr|mi.\u0283\u025bl \u0281u|}}; 19 April 1941 \u2013 11 March 2020), also known as '''Michel Roux Snr.''', was a French [[chef]] and [[restaurateur]] working in Britain. Along with his brother [[Albert Roux|Albert]], he opened [[Le Gavroche]], later to become the first three [[Michelin star]]red restaurant in Britain, and [[The Waterside Inn]], which was the first restaurant outside France to hold three stars for 25 years.\n\nRoux followed his brother into becoming a [[pastry chef]], and again to England in order to open their first restaurant. Together they have been described as the \"godfathers of modern restaurant cuisine in the UK\", and Roux was inducted into several French [[Order (decoration)|orders]], and received two lifetime achievement awards from different publications. He was decorated during a period of National Service for France during the 1960s.\n\nHe founded the [[Roux Brothers Scholarship]] along with Albert in 1984, and worked as a consultant for companies such as [[British Airways]] and [[Celebrity Cruises]] over the years. After he and his brother split the business in 1986, Roux took the Waterside Inn, which he handed over to his son, [[Alain Roux|Alain]], in 2002. He remained an active [[food writer]] and appeared on television shows such as ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'', ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]]'' and the Roux family-centric series ''The Roux Legacy'', and on the ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' programme on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04hz49k|title=Woman's Hour, BBC Radio 4|work=BBC|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMichel Roux was born on 19 April 1941 in [[Charolles]], [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]], in a room above his grandfather's [[charcuterie]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Grimes|first=William|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/obituaries/michel-roux-dead.html|title=Michel Roux, 78, Dies; Helped Bring French Cuisine to London|date=14 March 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=16 April 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> (a delicatessen specializing in meat products). He moved to Paris with his family after the war, where his father Michel set up his own charcuterie, after not taking over the family business in Charolles. His father gambled away all of the family's money, and the shop was closed to prevent it from going [[bankrupt]]. By the time Roux turned ten, his father had left the family and was not heard from again.<ref name=zesouffle>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|title='I love ze souffle, eet reminds me of ze boobs of ze woman'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2004/jul/11/foodanddrink.features9|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=11 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRoux's older brother [[Albert Roux|Albert]] had already become a patissier ([[pastry chef]]), and Roux followed him into this field at the age of fourteen. He became an apprentice to [[Camille Loyal]] in [[Belleville, Paris|Belleville]], working seventy-hour weeks. Roux's tasks at the [[p\u00e2tisserie]] included making up to sixty [[galette des rois|galettes des rois]] over the course of three days for [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]]. Albert found Roux further employment as his apprenticeship ended. As Albert was working at the British Embassy in Paris as a [[sous chef]], Roux joined him there as the pastry chef for the Embassy. He moved on from there to become a chef in [[Philippe de Rothschild]]'s service, while Albert moved to England to work there.<ref name=zesouffle/> \n\nBetween 1960 and 1962, Roux served his [[Conscription in France|French National Service]]. He was first stationed at the [[Palace of Versailles]], but was later posted overseas in [[B\u00e9char]], Algeria. He was awarded the [[M\u00e9daille comm\u00e9morative des op\u00e9rations de s\u00e9curit\u00e9 et de maintien de l'ordre en Afrique du Nord]].<ref name=debretts>{{cite web|title=Michel Roux, Esq, OBE|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/7775/Michel+Andr%C3%A9.aspx|publisher=Debretts|accessdate=19 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105104811/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/7775/Michel+Andr%C3%A9.aspx|archivedate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[image:Michel Roux - Pastry 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Michel Roux making pastry in 2009]]\nRoux nearly decided to give up cooking to become an [[opera singer]],<ref name=radiolegacy>{{cite news|last=Webb|first=Claire|title=The Roux Legacy revealed|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-02-05/the-roux-legacy-revealed|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 February 2012}}</ref> but instead followed Albert to London, despite not being able to speak English. He would later recall that people thought he was mad for travelling there in view of the fact that he considered the state of English cooking at the time to be horrific.<ref name=zesouffle/> \n\nIn 1967 the brothers opened their first restaurant, [[Le Gavroche]] at [[Lower Sloane Street]] in London.<ref name=zesouffle/> The opening party was attended by celebrities such as [[Charlie Chaplin]] and [[Ava Gardner]]. For the following week, Chaplin was reportedly shuttled across London so he could eat there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Observer classic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2002/may/12/foodanddrink.features9|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=12 May 2002}}</ref> In 1972 the brothers opened a second restaurant, the [[Waterside Inn]], in [[Bray, Berkshire]],<ref name=zesouffle/> and launched a catering business.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk>{{cite news|title=Albert and Michel Roux|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/Articles/19/05/2005/300524/Albert-and-Michel-Roux.htm|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Caterer and Hotelkeeper|date=12 May 2005}}</ref> \n\nIn 1974, when [[Michelin star]]s were first awarded in the UK, Le Gavroche and the Waterside Inn both won a star, and when a number of restaurants won two Michelin stars for the first time in 1977, both Roux restaurants were among them. Le Gavroche moved to a new location in [[Mayfair]] in 1982, and in the same year became the first restaurant in the UK to be awarded three Michelin stars. The same rating for the Waterside Inn followed in 1985, but Le Gavroche went back down to two stars in 1993 and has not regained the three star level. In 2010, the Waterside Inn became the first restaurant outside France to have held three Michelin stars for a period of 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelin stars in London|url=http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-lon.htm|publisher=Michelin Online|accessdate=19 August 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130114023315/http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-lon.htm|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Michelin stars in England|url=http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-eng.htm|publisher=Michelin Online|accessdate=19 August 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michel and Alain Roux celebrate 25 years of three Michelin stars at the Waterside Inn|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2010/05/michel-and-alain-roux-celebrate-25-years-of-three-michelin-stars-at-the-waterside-inn-1.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Guide Girl|date=19 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816090924/http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2010/05/michel-and-alain-roux-celebrate-25-years-of-three-michelin-stars-at-the-waterside-inn-1.html|archive-date=16 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Roux Brothers Scholarship]] was founded by Albert and Michel in 1984. It is an annual competition to select a single chef to send out as an apprentice.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /> The first winner was [[Andrew Fairlie (chef)|Andrew Fairlie]], and winners over the years have included [[Sat Bains]] (1999) and Simon Hulstone (2003).<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Winners|url=http://www.rouxscholarship.co.uk/roux_scholarship_winners.php|publisher=The Roux Scholarship|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn 1986 the brothers split their restaurant business between them, following a disagreement over the direction that their joint business should take; Albert took Le Gavroche, while Michel took the Waterside Inn.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /> Michel was a consultant to [[British Airways]] for twenty years between 1983 and 2003, and for [[Celebrity Cruises]] since 1990. The Roux brothers' catering company was purchased by [[Compass Group]] in 1993, with Albert retained as a consultant.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk />\n\nRoux's son, [[Alain Roux]], currently runs the Waterside Inn in Bray, having taken over as chef patron in 2002.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /><ref>{{cite news|last=Ruddick|first=Peter|title=Alain Roux on three Michelin stars: Things are never for life|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/People/Alain-Roux-on-three-Michelin-stars-Things-are-never-for-life|accessdate=11 August 2012|newspaper=Big Hospitality|date=16 May 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2008, Roux announced that he would move permanently to [[Crans-Montana]], Switzerland, citing concerns about the state of public safety in Britain. He also owned a vineyard and house on the [[Cote d'Azur]] in France.<ref name=\"dteljul08\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2444180/Michel-Roux%2C-French-chef%2C-quits-Britain-for-safer-Switzerland.html|title=Michel Roux, French chef, quits Britain for safer Switzerland|last=Alleyne |first=Richard|date=22 July 2008|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, Roux worked with British baking company, Bakedin, as a consultant reviewing and approving all recipes.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bakedin Baking Club|url=https://bakedin.co.uk/pages/baking-club|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Television and radio work===\nRoux spoke out against entertainment-type cooking shows such as the 1990s cooking gameshow ''[[Can't Cook, Won't Cook]]'', saying that \"The way these people handle food is a crime. They don't even know the basics. Little attention is paid to detail. Instead, they are intent on having a giggle and a joke. They can do this without involving food.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Cooking up a storm in the TV kitchen|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/186941.stm|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=5 October 1998}}</ref> The Roux brothers had a [[BBC]] television show, ''At Home with the Roux Brothers'', in the early eighties.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gilbert |first1=Gerard |title=The Roux dynasty: Too many cooks? Mais non! |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-roux-dynasty-too-many-cooks-mais-non-6296325.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |publisher=Independent |date=29 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nTogether with his brother Albert, Roux appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 26 October 1986.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michel Roux|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/topics/michel_roux|publisher=BBC Programmes|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> The [[Good Food]] channel aired a five-part series entitled ''[[The Roux Legacy]]'' in January 2012, which featured both brothers, along with their sons Michel Jr. and Alain. Roux had also appeared as a guest judge on ''[[MasterChef: The Professionals]]'', alongside his nephew Michel Jr,<ref>{{cite news|title=Steve Groves of Launceston Place wins Masterchef: The Professionals|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2009/10/steve-groves-of-launceston-place-wins-masterchef-the-professionals.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Guide Girl|date=22 October 2009}}</ref> and on ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'' alongside his son Alain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saturday Kitchen this weekend|url=http://www.ollysmith.com/olly-to-appear-on-saturday-kitchen-this-weekend-3645/|publisher=OllySmith.com|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy and awards===\nRoux and his brother have been called the \"godfathers of modern restaurant cuisine in the UK\" by [[hospitality]] industry magazine ''[[Caterer and Hotelkeeper]]'', while ''[[The Observer Food Monthly]]'' described him as \"perhaps the finest pastry chef this country has ever had\" when he was awarded their Lifetime Achievement Award in 2011.<ref name=lifetime2011>{{cite news|last=Hopkinson|first=Simon|title=Observer Food Monthly Awards 2011 Lifetime Achievement: Michel Roux Snr|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/16/ofm-awards-lifetime-michel-roux|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=16 October 2011}}</ref> Roux had previously won the Lifetime Achievement award from ''[[Tatler (1901)|Tatler]]'' magazine in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=In the September issue: Tatler Restaurant Awards|url=http://www.tatler.com/bystander/events/2012/july/tatler-restaurant-awards#/8219/image/1|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Tatler|date=1 August 2012}}</ref> In a poll of UK chefs carried out by ''Caterer and Hotelkeeper'' magazine in 2003, the Roux brothers were voted the most influential chefs in the country, and in 2004 Michel Roux was voted the [[The Automobile Association|AA]] Chef's Chef.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk />\n\nMany well known chefs have been trained by one or the other of the Roux brothers, with Michel estimating in 2010 that \"Half of the Michelin star-holders in Britain come from either my brother's kitchen or my kitchen\".<ref name=gordontruth/> These have included [[Gordon Ramsay]], [[Marco Pierre White]],<ref name=gordontruth/> and [[Pierre Koffman]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Michel Roux Snr|url = http://goodfood.uktv.co.uk|publisher = Good Food|accessdate = 19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nRoux was awarded the [[Meilleur Ouvrier de France]] en P\u00e2tisserie in 1976. He was a member of several [[Order (decoration)|orders]] in France. In 1987, he was inducted into the [[National Order of Merit (France)|National Order of Merit]] as a Chevalier (knight), and into the [[M\u00e9rite agricole]] as an officer. In 1990 he was made a Chevalier in the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], and in 2004 the [[Legion of Honour]] followed. Outside France he was made an honorary [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in 2002, and was made an [[Honorary doctorate|honorary Doctor]] of Culinary Arts by the [[University of Rhode Island]] in the same year.<ref name=debretts />\n\n====Military awards====\n<center>[[File:Medaille commemorative des Operations de securite et de Maintien de l'ordre ribbon.svg|106px]]<br>[[North Africa Security and Order Operations Commemorative Medal]]<br><small>[[France|FR]]: M\u00e9daille comm\u00e9morative des op\u00e9rations de s\u00e9curit\u00e9 et de maintien de l'ordre en Afrique du Nord\n</small></center>\n\n==Personal life==\nMichel Roux was the brother of [[Albert Roux]]. Michel had a son named [[Alain Roux]], while Albert's son is [[Michel Roux Jr.]].<ref name=educated>{{cite news|last=Thring|first=Oliver|title=How the Roux family educated the British palate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/apr/21/roux-brothers-influence-britain|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 April 2011}}</ref> When Alain was ten years old, Roux and his wife divorced, with his wife taking British-born Alain and his two sisters to France. Alain would visit during the school holidays and work with Michel in the kitchens, and decided at the age of fourteen that he wanted to become a chef like his father.<ref name=radiolegacy/> \n\nRoux met his second wife (1984\u20132017)<ref name=Thecaterer2017>{{cite news|last=Harmer|first=Janet|title=Robyn Roux, wife of Michel, has died|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/restaurant/robyn-roux-wife-of-michel-has-died|accessdate=17 November 2017|newspaper=The Caterer|date=17 November 2017}}</ref> Robyn Joyce, after being set up on a blind date with her by former apprentice Leigh Stone-Herbert in [[Sydney]], Australia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robyn Roux gives her first interview|url=http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/nl224.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Financial Times|date=13 December 2003}}</ref> The relationship has been credited with opening the door to Australian chefs being trained by the Roux brothers.<ref name=gordontruth>{{cite news|last=Rowe|first=Michelle|title=The truth about Gordon|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/food-wine/the-truth-about-gordon/story-e6frg8jo-1225827047282|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Australian|date=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nMichel Roux died on the night of 11 March 2020, at home in [[Bray, Berkshire]], aged 78, following a history of [[idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis]].<ref name=Thecaterer2020>{{cite news|last=Price|first=Katherine|title=\nMichel Roux dies aged 79|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/michel-roux-dies-obituary|accessdate=12 March 2020|newspaper=The Caterer|date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date= 12 March 2020 |title= Michel Roux: French restaurateur and chef dies aged 78 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-51856312 |work= BBC News |access-date= 14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michelroux-obe.com/ Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|2465672}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roux, Michel}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths in South East England]]\n[[Category:People from Charolles]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:French chefs]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Agricultural Merit]]\n[[Category:Head chefs of Michelin starred restaurants]]\n[[Category:Honorary Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:French restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Roux family]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French chef}}\n{{other people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox chef <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox chef/doc]] -->\n| name           = Michel Roux\n| image          = Michel Roux.jpg\n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = Michel Roux in 2008\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|df=yes|1941|4|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Charolles]], France\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|3|11|1941|4|19}}\n| death_place    = [[Bray, Berkshire]], England\n| ratings        = {{plainlist|\n*[[Michelin star]]s {{Rating|3|3}} (1974&ndash;2002)\n}}\n| prevrests      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Le Gavroche]]\n*[[The Waterside Inn]]\n}}\n| awards         = {{plainlist|\n*[[Meilleur Ouvrier de France]]\n*2008 Lifetime Achievement award by ''[[Tatler (1901)|Tatler]]''\n*2011 Lifetime Achievement award by ''[[The Observer Food Monthly]]''\n}}\n| website = {{Official URL|http://www.michelroux-obe.com}}\n}}\n'''Michel Roux''', [[OBE]] ({{IPA-fr|mi.\u0283\u025bl \u0281u|}}; 19 April 1941 \u2013 11 March 2020), also known as '''Michel Roux Snr.''', was a French [[chef]] and [[restaurateur]] working in Britain. Along with his brother [[Albert Roux|Albert]], he opened [[Le Gavroche]], later to become the first three [[Michelin star]]red restaurant in Britain, and [[The Waterside Inn]], which was the first restaurant outside France to hold three stars for 25 years.\n\nRoux followed his brother into becoming a [[pastry chef]], and again to England in order to open their first restaurant. Together they have been described as the \"godfathers of modern restaurant cuisine in the UK\", and Roux was inducted into several French [[Order (decoration)|orders]], and received two lifetime achievement awards from different publications. He was decorated during a period of National Service for France during the 1960s.\n\nHe founded the [[Roux Brothers Scholarship]] along with Albert in 1984, and worked as a consultant for companies such as [[British Airways]] and [[Celebrity Cruises]] over the years. After he and his brother split the business in 1986, Roux took the Waterside Inn, which he handed over to his son, [[Alain Roux|Alain]], in 2002. He remained an active [[food writer]] and appeared on television shows such as ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'', ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]]'' and the Roux family-centric series ''The Roux Legacy'', and on the ''[[Woman's Hour]]'' programme on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04hz49k|title=Woman's Hour, BBC Radio 4|work=BBC|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMichel Roux was born on 19 April 1941 in [[Charolles]], [[Sa\u00f4ne-et-Loire]], in a room above his grandfather's [[charcuterie]]<ref>{{Cite news|last=Grimes|first=William|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/14/obituaries/michel-roux-dead.html|title=Michel Roux, 78, Dies; Helped Bring French Cuisine to London|date=2020-03-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-16|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> (a delicatessen specializing in meat products). He moved to Paris with his family after the war, where his father Michel set up his own charcuterie, after not taking over the family business in Charolles. His father gambled away all of the family's money, and the shop was closed to prevent it from going [[bankrupt]]. By the time Roux turned ten, his father had left the family and was not heard from again.<ref name=zesouffle>{{cite news|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|title='I love ze souffle, eet reminds me of ze boobs of ze woman'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2004/jul/11/foodanddrink.features9|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=11 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRoux's older brother [[Albert Roux|Albert]] had already become a patissier ([[pastry chef]]), and Roux followed him into this field at the age of fourteen. He became an apprentice to [[Camille Loyal]] in [[Belleville, Paris|Belleville]], working seventy-hour weeks. Roux's tasks at the [[p\u00e2tisserie]] included making up to sixty [[galette des rois|galettes des rois]] over the course of three days for [[Epiphany (holiday)|Epiphany]]. Albert found Roux further employment as his apprenticeship ended. As Albert was working at the British Embassy in Paris as a [[sous chef]], Roux joined him there as the pastry chef for the Embassy. He moved on from there to become a chef in [[Philippe de Rothschild]]'s service, while Albert moved to England to work there.<ref name=zesouffle/> \n\nBetween 1960 and 1962, Roux served his [[Conscription in France|French National Service]]. He was first stationed at the [[Palace of Versailles]], but was later posted overseas in [[B\u00e9char]], Algeria. He was awarded the [[M\u00e9daille comm\u00e9morative des op\u00e9rations de s\u00e9curit\u00e9 et de maintien de l'ordre en Afrique du Nord]].<ref name=debretts>{{cite web|title=Michel Roux, Esq, OBE|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/7775/Michel+Andr%C3%A9.aspx|publisher=Debretts|accessdate=19 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105104811/http://www.debretts.com/people/biographies/browse/r/7775/Michel+Andr%C3%A9.aspx|archivedate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[image:Michel Roux - Pastry 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Michel Roux making pastry in 2009]]\nRoux nearly decided to give up cooking to become an [[opera singer]],<ref name=radiolegacy>{{cite news|last=Webb|first=Claire|title=The Roux Legacy revealed|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-02-05/the-roux-legacy-revealed|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Radio Times|date=5 February 2012}}</ref> but instead followed Albert to London, despite not being able to speak English. He would later recall that people thought he was mad for travelling there in view of the fact that he considered the state of English cooking at the time to be horrific.<ref name=zesouffle/> \n\nIn 1967 the brothers opened their first restaurant, [[Le Gavroche]] at [[Lower Sloane Street]] in London.<ref name=zesouffle/> The opening party was attended by celebrities such as [[Charlie Chaplin]] and [[Ava Gardner]]. For the following week, Chaplin was reportedly shuttled across London so he could eat there.<ref>{{cite news|title=Observer classic|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2002/may/12/foodanddrink.features9|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=12 May 2002}}</ref> In 1972 the brothers opened a second restaurant, the [[Waterside Inn]], in [[Bray, Berkshire]],<ref name=zesouffle/> and launched a catering business.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk>{{cite news|title=Albert and Michel Roux|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/Articles/19/05/2005/300524/Albert-and-Michel-Roux.htm|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Caterer and Hotelkeeper|date=12 May 2005}}</ref> \n\nIn 1974, when [[Michelin star]]s were first awarded in the UK, Le Gavroche and the Waterside Inn both won a star, and when a number of restaurants won two Michelin stars for the first time in 1977, both Roux restaurants were among them. Le Gavroche moved to a new location in [[Mayfair]] in 1982, and in the same year became the first restaurant in the UK to be awarded three Michelin stars. The same rating for the Waterside Inn followed in 1985, but Le Gavroche went back down to two stars in 1993 and has not regained the three star level. In 2010, the Waterside Inn became the first restaurant outside France to have held three Michelin stars for a period of 25 years.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michelin stars in London|url=http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-lon.htm|publisher=Michelin Online|accessdate=19 August 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130114023315/http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-lon.htm|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Michelin stars in England|url=http://www.michelinonline.co.uk/travelshop/star-history/rg-eng.htm|publisher=Michelin Online|accessdate=19 August 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Michel and Alain Roux celebrate 25 years of three Michelin stars at the Waterside Inn|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2010/05/michel-and-alain-roux-celebrate-25-years-of-three-michelin-stars-at-the-waterside-inn-1.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Guide Girl|date=19 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816090924/http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2010/05/michel-and-alain-roux-celebrate-25-years-of-three-michelin-stars-at-the-waterside-inn-1.html|archive-date=16 August 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Roux Brothers Scholarship]] was founded by Albert and Michel in 1984. It is an annual competition to select a single chef to send out as an apprentice.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /> The first winner was [[Andrew Fairlie (chef)|Andrew Fairlie]], and winners over the years have included [[Sat Bains]] (1999) and Simon Hulstone (2003).<ref>{{cite web|title=Past Winners|url=http://www.rouxscholarship.co.uk/roux_scholarship_winners.php|publisher=The Roux Scholarship|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn 1986 the brothers split their restaurant business between them, following a disagreement over the direction that their joint business should take; Albert took Le Gavroche, while Michel took the Waterside Inn.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /> Michel was a consultant to [[British Airways]] for twenty years between 1983 and 2003, and for [[Celebrity Cruises]] since 1990. The Roux brothers' catering company was purchased by [[Compass Group]] in 1993, with Albert retained as a consultant.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk />\n\nRoux's son, [[Alain Roux]], currently runs the Waterside Inn in Bray, having taken over as chef patron in 2002.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk /><ref>{{cite news|last=Ruddick|first=Peter|title=Alain Roux on three Michelin stars: Things are never for life|url=http://www.bighospitality.co.uk/People/Alain-Roux-on-three-Michelin-stars-Things-are-never-for-life|accessdate=11 August 2012|newspaper=Big Hospitality|date=16 May 2012}}</ref> \n\nIn July 2008, Roux announced that he would move permanently to [[Crans-Montana]], Switzerland, citing concerns about the state of public safety in Britain. He also owned a vineyard and house on the [[Cote d'Azur]] in France.<ref name=\"dteljul08\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/2444180/Michel-Roux%2C-French-chef%2C-quits-Britain-for-safer-Switzerland.html|title=Michel Roux, French chef, quits Britain for safer Switzerland|last=Alleyne |first=Richard|date=22 July 2008|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nSince 2014, Roux worked with British baking company, Bakedin, as a consultant reviewing and approving all recipes.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bakedin Baking Club|url=https://bakedin.co.uk/pages/baking-club|accessdate=5 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Television and radio work===\nRoux spoke out against entertainment-type cooking shows such as the 1990s cooking gameshow ''[[Can't Cook, Won't Cook]]'', saying that \"The way these people handle food is a crime. They don't even know the basics. Little attention is paid to detail. Instead, they are intent on having a giggle and a joke. They can do this without involving food.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Cooking up a storm in the TV kitchen|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/186941.stm|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=BBC News|date=5 October 1998}}</ref> The Roux brothers had a [[BBC]] television show, ''At Home with the Roux Brothers'', in the early eighties.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gilbert |first1=Gerard |title=The Roux dynasty: Too many cooks? Mais non! |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/the-roux-dynasty-too-many-cooks-mais-non-6296325.html |accessdate=12 March 2020 |publisher=Independent |date=29 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nTogether with his brother Albert, Roux appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on 26 October 1986.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michel Roux|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/topics/michel_roux|publisher=BBC Programmes|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref> The [[Good Food]] channel aired a five-part series entitled ''[[The Roux Legacy]]'' in January 2012, which featured both brothers, along with their sons Michel Jr. and Alain. Roux had also appeared as a guest judge on ''[[MasterChef: The Professionals]]'', alongside his nephew Michel Jr,<ref>{{cite news|title=Steve Groves of Launceston Place wins Masterchef: The Professionals|url=http://www.caterersearch.com/blogs/guide-girl/2009/10/steve-groves-of-launceston-place-wins-masterchef-the-professionals.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Guide Girl|date=22 October 2009}}</ref> and on ''[[Saturday Kitchen]]'' alongside his son Alain.<ref>{{cite web|title=Saturday Kitchen this weekend|url=http://www.ollysmith.com/olly-to-appear-on-saturday-kitchen-this-weekend-3645/|publisher=OllySmith.com|accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Legacy and awards===\nRoux and his brother have been called the \"godfathers of modern restaurant cuisine in the UK\" by [[hospitality]] industry magazine ''[[Caterer and Hotelkeeper]]'', while ''[[The Observer Food Monthly]]'' described him as \"perhaps the finest pastry chef this country has ever had\" when he was awarded their Lifetime Achievement Award in 2011.<ref name=lifetime2011>{{cite news|last=Hopkinson|first=Simon|title=Observer Food Monthly Awards 2011 Lifetime Achievement: Michel Roux Snr|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/16/ofm-awards-lifetime-michel-roux|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Observer|date=16 October 2011}}</ref> Roux had previously won the Lifetime Achievement award from ''[[Tatler (1901)|Tatler]]'' magazine in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=In the September issue: Tatler Restaurant Awards|url=http://www.tatler.com/bystander/events/2012/july/tatler-restaurant-awards#/8219/image/1|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Tatler|date=1 August 2012}}</ref> In a poll of UK chefs carried out by ''Caterer and Hotelkeeper'' magazine in 2003, the Roux brothers were voted the most influential chefs in the country, and in 2004 Michel Roux was voted the [[The Automobile Association|AA]] Chef's Chef.<ref name=albmichbio2005c&hk />\n\nMany well known chefs have been trained by one or the other of the Roux brothers, with Michel estimating in 2010 that \"Half of the Michelin star-holders in Britain come from either my brother's kitchen or my kitchen\".<ref name=gordontruth/> These have included [[Gordon Ramsay]], [[Marco Pierre White]],<ref name=gordontruth/> and [[Pierre Koffman]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Michel Roux Snr|url = http://goodfood.uktv.co.uk|publisher = Good Food|accessdate = 19 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nRoux was awarded the [[Meilleur Ouvrier de France]] en P\u00e2tisserie in 1976. He was a member of several [[Order (decoration)|orders]] in France. In 1987, he was inducted into the [[National Order of Merit (France)|National Order of Merit]] as a Chevalier (knight), and into the [[M\u00e9rite agricole]] as an officer. In 1990 he was made a Chevalier in the [[Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], and in 2004 the [[Legion of Honour]] followed. Outside France he was made an honorary [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in 2002, and was made an [[Honorary doctorate|honorary Doctor]] of Culinary Arts by the [[University of Rhode Island]] in the same year.<ref name=debretts />\n\n====Military awards====\n<center>[[File:Medaille commemorative des Operations de securite et de Maintien de l'ordre ribbon.svg|106px]]<br>[[North Africa Security and Order Operations Commemorative Medal]]<br><small>[[France|FR]]: M\u00e9daille comm\u00e9morative des op\u00e9rations de s\u00e9curit\u00e9 et de maintien de l'ordre en Afrique du Nord\n</small></center>\n\n==Personal life==\nMichel Roux was the brother of [[Albert Roux]]. Michel had a son named [[Alain Roux]], while Albert's son is [[Michel Roux Jr.]].<ref name=educated>{{cite news|last=Thring|first=Oliver|title=How the Roux family educated the British palate|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2011/apr/21/roux-brothers-influence-britain|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=21 April 2011}}</ref> When Alain was ten years old, Roux and his wife divorced, with his wife taking British-born Alain and his two sisters to France. Alain would visit during the school holidays and work with Michel in the kitchens, and decided at the age of fourteen that he wanted to become a chef like his father.<ref name=radiolegacy/> \n\nRoux met his second wife (1984\u20132017)<ref name=Thecaterer2017>{{cite news|last=Harmer|first=Janet|title=Robyn Roux, wife of Michel, has died|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/restaurant/robyn-roux-wife-of-michel-has-died|accessdate=17 November 2017|newspaper=The Caterer|date=17 November 2017}}</ref> Robyn Joyce, after being set up on a blind date with her by former apprentice Leigh Stone-Herbert in [[Sydney]], Australia.<ref>{{cite news|title=Robyn Roux gives her first interview|url=http://www.jancisrobinson.com/articles/nl224.html|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=Financial Times|date=13 December 2003}}</ref> The relationship has been credited with opening the door to Australian chefs being trained by the Roux brothers.<ref name=gordontruth>{{cite news|last=Rowe|first=Michelle|title=The truth about Gordon|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/food-wine/the-truth-about-gordon/story-e6frg8jo-1225827047282|accessdate=19 August 2012|newspaper=The Australian|date=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nMichel Roux died on the night of 11 March 2020, at home in [[Bray, Berkshire]], aged 78, following a history of [[idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis]].<ref name=Thecaterer2020>{{cite news|last=Price|first=Katherine|title=\nMichel Roux dies aged 79|url=https://www.thecaterer.com/news/michel-roux-dies-obituary|accessdate=12 March 2020|newspaper=The Caterer|date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date= 12 March 2020 |title= Michel Roux: French restaurateur and chef dies aged 78 |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-berkshire-51856312 |work= BBC News |access-date= 14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.michelroux-obe.com/ Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|2465672}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roux, Michel}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths in South East England]]\n[[Category:People from Charolles]]\n[[Category:French emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:French chefs]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Agricultural Merit]]\n[[Category:Head chefs of Michelin starred restaurants]]\n[[Category:Honorary Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:French restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Roux family]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michel_Roux"}
{"title_page": "List of Bollywood Muslim Actresses", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\nThis is the list of notable Muslim actresses (especially old-time Actresses) who have starred in [[Bollywood]] films as leading roles. the aim of this article to provide the information for their fan who doesn't know her original name due to change their original(birth) name to screen name and people know them by the screen name. Many of them especially old-time actresses were belonging to the Royal Family ancestor. Their Royal beauty makes them different from other actresses. As like [[Parveen_Babi#External_links|Parveeb Babi]]   [[Sultana_(actress)|Sultana]]  [[Zubeida]]  [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatma_Begum|Fatma Begum]] [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naseem_Banu|Naseem Banu]][[Nimmi ]] [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mehtab_(actress)|Mehtab_(actress)]] [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soha_Ali_Khan|Soha Ali Khan]][[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sara_Ali_Khan|Sara Ali Khan Pataudi]]\n\n==1920s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1922\n|[[Fatma Begum]]\n|Veer Abhimanyu\n|-\n|[[Sultana (actress)|Sultana]]\n|Veer Abhimanyu\n|-\n|1923\n|[[Zubeida]]\n|Kohinoor\n|-\n|1926\n|[[Gohar Mamajiwala]]\n|Baap Kamai\n|-\n|}\n\n==1930s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1930\n|-\n|[[Mehtab (actress)|Mehtab]]\n|Kamaal-e-Shamsheer \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |1931\n|[[Esther Victoria Abraham]]\n|Toofani Tiruni\n|-\n|[[Kajjanbai]]\n|[[Shirin Farhad (1931 film)|Shirin Farhad]]\n|-\n|[[Khursheed Bano]]\n|Eye for an eye\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |1932\n|[[Firoza Begum (actress)|Firoza Begum]]\n|Bewafa Qatil\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1933\